%md
## K-means clustering for customers based on arrengements and transactions

This is report for a clustering model of customers based on two attributes: Number of Arrangemens
and Transactions of those arrangements for the month Octomber. The data are stored in Hadoop installation 
on perfman11 and Spark with python are used to create the model and visualitations.

paragraphs.title: Ploting data from Hive metastore with Impala with Zeppelin tools
paragraphs.text:
%jdbc(impala)
use customer;

select 
t1.customercrs as crs, arCount , trAmoun
from (select customercrs,
     count(customercrs) as arCount 
     from arrangements
     group by customercrs) as t1
join (
    select  ar.customercrs, sum(tf.trans_amount) as trAmoun
    from customer.arrangements as ar
    inner join customer.trans_fact_table as tf 
    on ar.arrangementid = tf.arrangementid 
    group by customercrs
    ) as t2
on t1.customercrs = t2.customercrs

msg.data: Query executed successfully. Affected rows : -1

paragraphs.title: Data fetching from Hive metastore
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
#Create two separe df and join them with spark
#More readable than single spark sql query

print'Pyspark Version is',spark.version

df_1 = spark.sql("select customercrs, count(customercrs) as arCount from customer.arrangements group by customercrs")
df_2 = spark.sql("select  ar.customercrs, ar.productlevel1, sum(tf.trans_amount) as trAmount from customer.arrangements \
                    as ar inner join customer.trans_fact_table as tf \
                    on ar.arrangementid = tf.arrangementid group by customercrs, ar.productlevel1") 
                    

dfOrig = df_1.join(df_2,df_1.customercrs == df_2.customercrs, 'inner').drop(df_1.customercrs)

print 'Dataset has intially' , dfOrig.count(), 'values'

paragraphs.title: Create ML Dataframe
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from pyspark.sql import DataFrameStatFunctions as statFunc
from pyspark.ml.clustering import KMeans
from pyspark.ml.linalg import Vectors
from pyspark.ml.feature import VectorAssembler

#Rename columns to feature1,2
df = df.withColumnRenamed('arCount','f1')
df = df.withColumnRenamed('trAmount','f2')

%md 
To avoid outliers we can trim the dataset for extreme values from training process and analyse 
them seperately to find out if they are outliers, data errors or corrupted values. 
So in traing we crop the top and bottom 2% from transactions amount

paragraphs.title: Triming the dataset
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

[cutoff_low,cutoof_high] = statFunc(df).approxQuantile( 'f2', [ 0.02 , 0.98], 0.05)

print "Cutoff points (0.02 and 0.98 quantiles) for transaction amounts are:"

print [cutoff_low,cutoof_high]

df_trimmed = df.filter( (df["f2"] > cutoff_low) & (df["f2"] < cutoof_high) )
#df_trimmed = df_trimmed.select(["f1","f2"]) #Add customer CRS <<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<for 29/12

print"Final dataframe has",df_trimmed.count()

paragraphs.title: Vectorise Features
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

vec_assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols = df_trimmed.select(["f1","f2"]).columns, outputCol='features')
final_data = vec_assembler.transform(df_trimmed)

paragraphs.title: Scale Features to [0-1]
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

from pyspark.ml.feature import StandardScaler
scaler = StandardScaler(inputCol="features", outputCol="scaledFeatures", withStd=True, withMean=False)

scalerModel = scaler.fit(final_data)
final_data = scalerModel.transform(final_data)

final_data.select(["f1","f2","features","scaledFeatures"]).show(2,False)

paragraphs.title: Model training
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

import random
random.seed(9999)

models = []

for centers in [2,3,4,5]:
    kmeans = KMeans(featuresCol='scaledFeatures',k=centers)
    models.append(kmeans.fit(final_data))
    print("Finished Training for "+str(centers) + " centers")

paragraphs.title: Prepare Data for vizualitation
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

from pyspark.sql.functions import col, create_map, lit
from itertools import chain

red = '#cc0000'
blue = '#367bb9'
black = '#000000'

colMap = {0:red, 1:black, 2:blue}

color_expr = create_map([lit(x) for x in chain(*colMap.items())])
predictions = predictions.withColumn("color", color_expr.getItem(col("prediction")))

y = predictions.select("f1").dropna().rdd.flatMap(lambda x: x).collect()
x = predictions.select("f2").dropna().rdd.flatMap(lambda x: x).collect()

colors = predictions.select("color").dropna().rdd.flatMap(lambda x: x).collect()

%md
We can see 3 different clusters.

- Customers with high positve Transaction Amounts and few arrangements [Custer 2 / Blue]
- Customers with average transactions amount (near zero or negative) and few arrangements [Cluster 1/ Black]
- Customers with many arrangements and balanced transactions amount [Cluster 0 /Red]

We can confirme this image from cluster statistics for each clustor with average transaction 
amount and average product arrangements

paragraphs.title: Cluster Statistics
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

import numpy as np
import pyspark.sql.functions as func
from pyspark.sql.types import FloatType

def median(values_list):
    med = np.median(values_list)
    return float(med)
	
udf_median = func.udf(median, FloatType())

grouped = predictions.groupBy("prediction")

counts = grouped.count()

meansArr = grouped.agg(func.format_number(func.mean('f1'),2).alias('Arr Mean'))
meansTr = grouped.agg(func.format_number(func.mean('f2'),2).alias('TrAmount Mean'))

medAr = grouped.agg(udf_median(func.collect_list(predictions.f1)).alias('Arr Median'))
medTr = grouped.agg(udf_median(func.collect_list(predictions.f2)).alias('TrAmount Median'))

stdAr = grouped.agg(func.format_number(func.stddev("f1"),2).alias("Arr STD"))
stdTr = grouped.agg(func.format_number(func.stddev("f2"),2).alias("TrAmount STD"))

stats = meansArr.join(counts,meansArr.prediction == counts.prediction,'inner').drop(counts.prediction)
stats = stats.join(medAr,stats.prediction == medAr.prediction,'inner').drop(medAr.prediction)
stats = stats.join(stdAr,stats.prediction == stdAr.prediction,'inner').drop(stdAr.prediction)

stats = stats.join(meansTr,stats.prediction == meansTr.prediction,'inner').drop(meansTr.prediction)
stats = stats.join(medTr,stats.prediction == medTr.prediction,'inner').drop(medTr.prediction)
stats = stats.join(stdTr,stats.prediction == stdTr.prediction,'inner').drop(stdTr.prediction)

orderCols = ['prediction' , 'count', 'Arr Mean', 'Arr Median', 'Arr STD','TrAmount Mean','TrAmount Median','TrAmount STD']
		
stats = stats.select([col for col in orderCols])

stats = stats.withColumnRenamed('prediction','Cluster')
stats = stats.withColumnRenamed('count','Size')

stats.orderBy("Cluster").show()

paragraphs.title: Data manipulation for trellis plot
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
import math 

predictions = predictions.withColumnRenamed("prediction","Cluster")
predictions = predictions.withColumnRenamed('productlevel1','Product_Category')

res = predictions.groupBy(["Product_Category","Cluster"]).count()

dfPd = res.toPandas()
dfPd['countLog'] = dfPd['count'].apply(lambda x: math.log10(x))

%md 
We can see that customers in Cluster 2 have exclusively Investment products
while in Cluster 1  we have a more balanced product representation and 
in cluster 0 we have a little skew over Investment products too
